    <methods>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <para>The UWBRAD was deployed at the Remote Sensing site, and it continuously monitored the sea ice at oblique observation angles (35 -50 off-nadir) from top of a 5-m long stationary mast. For calibration purposes, the radiometer antenna was directed towards the sky every 15 minutes and observed sky radiation for 5 minutes. The instrument generated medium rate brightness temperature data collected from its four radiometer channels (540, 900, 1380, 1740 MHz) every ~3.5 seconds.</para>
        </description>
      </methodStep>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <para>After the expedition, RFI detection and mitigation algorithms were used to discard the unwanted signals from the collected medium rate data. The internal (noise diode) and external (sky) calibrations were applied to the Level 1 data to process them to Level 2 and 3, respectively. Since the sky measurements were frequent enough, we used them to calibrate the sea ice emissions with one-hour-long windows. Finally, the Level 3 data were smoothed by applying a 100-sample running average. These algorithms were implemented through Matlab.</para>
        </description>
      </methodStep>
      <sampling>
        <studyExtent>
          <description>
            <para>The UWBRAD was operated at the remote sensing site on the ice floe during MOSAiC Expedition. The monitored region was a refrozen melt pond (second year ice) which was chosen as a suitable location due to its undeformed nature as well as its close proximity to the Polarstern for easy access. The ice thickness during the installation of the UWBRAD was ~70 cm, and the snow depth was ~15 cm. The ice kept growing throughout the measurements, but no deformation was experienced. The instrument sampled the sea ice radiation every ~3.5 seconds.</para>
          </description>
        </studyExtent>
        <samplingDescription>
          <para>No sampling description provided.</para>
        </samplingDescription>
      </sampling>
    </methods>
